// Table Page Blood Compatibility Anyone who qualifies can donate blood, but depending on your blood type, you can only receive certain types of blood, plasma, or platelets. Do you know your blood type? It is important to know because blood types can be compatible or not compatible with each other. There are eight different blood types, and they don\'t always match each other. Interestingly, people who have O-negative blood are considered universal donors for the entire population because they can donate blood to all types of blood groups.\n\nThere are four main blood types: A, B, AB and O. The combination of protein and sugar, which is called antigens, on the surface of red blood cells, are what make that blood type compatible or incompatible with other blood groups.\n\n• For example, if you are blood type A, you can only receive blood type A or blood type O. You cannot receive blood type B or blood group AB.\n• If you have blood type B, you can only receive blood type B or blood type O. You cannot receive blood type A or blood type AB.\n• If you have blood type AB blood, you can receive all blood groups.\n• If you have blood type O, you can only receive blood type O. Understand Request sent Your data will be automatically updated once the process is done OK
